\\subsection{Supplementary Web Application: UrbanAnts}
As a complement to the package, the \\pkg{UrbanAnts} Shiny app \\citep{Goncalves2025} (available at \\url{https://urbanants.shinyapps.io/UrbanAnts/}) provides an interactive interface to explore the urban ant database used to develop the built-in guild classification. Users can browse species records, examine functional guild assignments, and download the underlying data. This transparency enhances confidence in the classification and offers an educational tool for students and researchers.
\\section{Illustrative Example}
We demonstrate the package using a simulated dataset of 36 ant species with abundances typical of an Atlantic Forest fragment. The dataset includes exotic, endemic, and rare species, providing a comprehensive test case. The code below reproduces all analyses and figures shown in this article.
\\begin{Schunk}
\\begin{Sinput}
R> # Create example dataset
R> dados <- data.frame(
+   Atta_sexdens = 50,
+   Camponotus_atriceps = 40,
+   Crematogaster_sp = 35,
+   Cyphomyrmex_minutus = 30,
+   Cyphomyrmex_rimosus = 28,
+   Ectatomma_edentatum = 25,
+   Heteroponera_mayri = 22,
+   Holcoponera_striatula = 20,
+   Monomorium_floricola = 18,
+   Monomorium_pharaonis = 17,
+   Pheidole_megacephala = 16,
+   Strumigenys_emmae = 15,
+   Strumigenys_rogeri = 14,
+   Nylanderia_fulva = 13,
+   Odontomachus_chelifer = 12,
+   Oxyepoecus_reticulatus = 11,
+   Pachycondyla_striata = 10,
+   Apterostigma_serratum = 9,
+   Brachymyrmex_delabiei = 8,
+   Brachymyrmex_feitosai = 7,
+   Camponotus_fallatus = 6,
+   Camponotus_hermanni = 5,
+   Camponotus_xanthogaster = 4,
+   Pheidole_aberrans = 3,
+   Pheidole_fimbriata = 3,
+   Pheidole_obscurithorax = 2,
+   Pheidole_subarmata = 2,
