Núcleo de Ciências Ambientais\\
Universidade de Mogi das Cruzes\\
Av. Dr. Cândido Xavier de Almeida e Souza, 200\\
Mogi das Cruzes – São Paulo – 08780-911, Brazil\\
E-mail: \\email{debora\\_cog@outlook.com}
}
\\begin{document}
\\maketitle
\\section{Introduction}
The health of the ecosystem is a fundamental component in maintaining environmental balance and human well-being \\citep{Costanza2012, Marselle2021, Ran2021}. The integrity of natural and urban environments is directly related to the capacity of ecosystems to provide essential services, such as climate regulation, nutrient cycling, and biological control \\citep{Strassburg2020, Li2024}. However, rapid transformations associated with urban expansion, habitat fragmentation, and climate change have compromised these processes, making it increasingly urgent to monitor and assess environmental quality using reliable biological indicators \\citep{Gorain2021, GaticaSaavedra2023}.
In this context, the use of bioindicators has proven to be a fundamental tool for understanding the effects of environmental changes on biodiversity and ecosystem functioning \\citep{Dahiya2022, Chowdhury2023}. Among the various groups used, ants (Hymenoptera: Formicidae) stand out for their wide distribution, abundance, and sensitivity to environmental changes. These insects perform key ecological functions, such as soil aeration, decomposition, and predation, and respond rapidly to anthropogenic disturbances, making them excellent indicators of environmental quality \\citep{Alonso2000, Chamoli2023, Lutinski2024}.
The structure and composition of ant communities reflect the complexity and stability of the ecosystems in which they occur, and can reveal gradients of degradation or environmental recovery \\citep{Zina2021, Silva2025, Nuraeni2025}. For this reason, ant-based studies have been widely used in environmental impact assessments, monitoring of protected areas, and analyses of sustainability in urban landscapes \\citep{Lutinski2024}. Integrating this information not only allows understanding of the ecological responses of biological communities but also supports conservation and environmental management strategies \\citep{Santos2019, Almeida2024}.
Despite the widespread use of ants in ecological studies, the integration of functional and ecological information about these communities still faces significant methodological limitations. The classification of species into trophic guilds, as well as the identification of attributes such as invasion status, rarity, or endemism, is often based on scattered bibliographic sources, heterogeneous categorization systems, and subjective decisions by researchers \\citep{Andersen1995, Silvestre2003, DelToro2012, Brandao2012}. This lack of standardization hinders reproducibility, limits comparisons across studies, and increases the analytical effort required to incorporate functional information into quantitative approaches. Moreover, much of these classifications are still performed manually, which is especially problematic for studies with large numbers of species or broad spatial coverage. Thus, there is a growing demand for computational tools that systematize and automate the ecological classification of ants, promoting greater consistency, transparency, and efficiency in ecological analyses \\citep{McGill2006, Violle2007}.
To address this gap, we present \\pkg{AntClassify}, an \\proglang{R} package developed for the functional and ecological classification of ants. It integrates information on trophic guilds, endemism, rarity, and invasion status, drawing on curated databases that currently reflect the ant fauna of Brazil, with the understanding that users may extend or adapt the underlying data for other regions. The package standardizes and automates these classifications from occurrence or abundance data, offering an accessible, reproducible, and robust tool for ecological analyses. In this way, it contributes to biodiversity studies, environmental quality assessments, and conservation applications across a variety of ecosystems and geographic contexts.
\\section{The AntClassify Package}
\\subsection{Overview and Design}
\\pkg{AntClassify} is implemented in \\proglang{R} \\citep{RCore2024} and follows a modular design. The main function, \\code{antclassify()}, runs the full pipeline, while individual functions (e.g., \\code{assign_guild_ants()}, \\code{check_exotic_ants()}, \\code{check_endemic_atlantic_ants()}, \\code{check_rarity_atlantic_ants()}) allow users to apply specific components. The package expects a community matrix where rows represent sampling units (or a single row for a single community) and columns represent species, with abundance or presence–absence values. Species names must exactly match those in the internal reference databases; underscores are automatically converted to spaces within the package. Users can import data from external files (e.g., CSV, TXT, Excel) using standard \\proglang{R} functions such as \\code{read.csv()}, \\code{read.table()}, or \\code{readxl::read_excel()}, ensuring that column names are correctly formatted as species names.
\\subsection{Functional Guild Classification}
The classification of species into functional guilds is based on three published frameworks from the myrmecological literature: \\citet{Delabie2000} (litter ant communities in Atlantic Forest), \\citet{Silvestre2003} (functional groups in Cerrado), and \\citet{Silva2015} (trophic groups in poneromorph ants). Additionally, \\pkg{AntClassify} includes a novel guild classification derived from an extensive database of ant species occurring in urban environments in Brazil \\citep{GoncalvesUnpub}. This classification was developed using data from the \\pkg{UrbanAnts} Shiny app \\citep{Goncalves2025}, which compiles occurrence records from urban areas across the country.
When a species is not present in the underlying reference databases, the package assigns it the label “Unidentified Guild”. This transparent behavior allows users to identify taxa for which no guild information is currently available. Moreover, because some classification schemes may assign multiple guilds to a single genus (e.g., depending on ecological context or species-level variation), users are encouraged to consult the original literature for ambiguous cases. By automating these assignments while preserving flexibility, the package reduces manual effort and subjectivity, enhances reproducibility, and enables researchers to select the framework most appropriate for their dataset and research question.
\\subsection{Exotic Species Detection}
The function \\code{check_exotic_ants()} identifies species listed as exotic in Brazil based on the master’s thesis by \\citet{Vieira2025}. The detection relies on a curated database embedded in the package, ensuring offline functionality and consistent results. The output includes a table of exotic species with their abundances and a bar plot visualizing their relative frequencies.
\\subsection{Endemic Species of the Atlantic Forest}
\\code{check_endemic_atlantic_ants()} flags species that are endemic to the Brazilian Atlantic Forest biome according to the list published by \\citet{Silva2024}. As with exotic detection, the endemic species list is built into the package, eliminating the need for external lookups and enabling reproducible analyses even without internet access.
\\subsection{Rarity Classification}
Following the framework of \\citet{Silva2024}, \\code{check_rarity_atlantic_ants()} classifies species into rarity forms based on geographic distribution (restricted vs. widespread) and local abundance (rare vs. common). The output includes a summary table with rarity categories and a plot of species abundance distribution colored by rarity form. This classification helps identify vulnerable species and supports conservation prioritization.
\\subsection{Supplementary Web Application: UrbanAnts}
As a complement to the package, the \\pkg{UrbanAnts} Shiny app \\citep{Goncalves2025} (available at \\url{https://urbanants.shinyapps.io/UrbanAnts/}) provides an interactive interface to explore the urban ant database used to develop the built-in guild classification. Users can browse species records, examine functional guild assignments, and download the underlying data. This transparency enhances confidence in the classification and offers an educational tool for students and researchers.
\\section{Illustrative Example}
We demonstrate the package using a simulated dataset of 36 ant. The dataset includes exotic, endemic, and rare species, providing a comprehensive test case. The code below reproduces all analyses and figures shown in this article.
\\begin{Schunk}
\\begin{Sinput}
R> # Create example dataset
R> dados <- data.frame(
+   Atta_sexdens = 50,
+   Camponotus_atriceps = 40,
+   Crematogaster_sp = 35,
+   Cyphomyrmex_minutus = 30,
+   Cyphomyrmex_rimosus = 28,
+   Ectatomma_edentatum = 25,
+   Heteroponera_mayri = 22,
+   Holcoponera_striatula = 20,
+   Monomorium_floricola = 18,
+   Monomorium_pharaonis = 17,
+   Pheidole_megacephala = 16,
+   Strumigenys_emmae = 15,
+   Strumigenys_rogeri = 14,
+   Nylanderia_fulva = 13,
+   Odontomachus_chelifer = 12,
+   Oxyepoecus_reticulatus = 11,
+   Pachycondyla_striata = 10,
+   Apterostigma_serratum = 9,
+   Brachymyrmex_delabiei = 8,
+   Brachymyrmex_feitosai = 7,
+   Camponotus_fallatus = 6,
+   Camponotus_hermanni = 5,
+   Camponotus_xanthogaster = 4,
+   Pheidole_aberrans = 3,
+   Pheidole_fimbriata = 3,
+   Pheidole_obscurithorax = 2,
+   Pheidole_subarmata = 2,
+   Strumigenys_fridericimuelleri = 2,
+   Heteroponera_inermis = 2,
+   Oxyepoecus_browni = 2,
+   Sphinctomyrmex_stali = 1,
+   Strumigenys_sanctipauli = 1,
+   Brachymyrmex_micromegas = 1,
+   Camponotus_tripartitus = 1,
+   Diaphoromyrma_sofiae = 1
+ )
R> colnames(dados) <- gsub("_", " ", colnames(dados))
\\end{Sinput}
\\end{Schunk}
\\begin{Schunk}
\\begin{Sinput}
R> guilds <- assign_guild_ants(dados)
R> exotics <- check_exotic_ants(dados)
R> endemics <- check_endemic_atlantic_ants(dados)
R> rarity <- check_rarity_atlantic_ants(dados)
\\end{Sinput}
\\end{Schunk}
