\\subsection{Modular Use}
Researchers can also use individual functions. For example, to obtain only the functional guild classification:
\\begin{Schunk}
R> guilds_only <- assign_guild_ants(dados)
R> head(guilds_only$table[, c("species", "abundance", "antclassify_guild")])
\\end{Schunk}
\\noindent The first six rows are shown in Table~\\ref{tab:modular}.
\\begin{table}[htbp]
\\centering
\\scriptsize
\\caption{First six rows of the functional guild classification using the individual function.}\\label{tab:modular}
\\begin{tabular}{p{2.5cm} r p{5cm}}
\\toprule
species & abundance & antclassify\\_guild \\\\
\\midrule
Atta sexdens & 50 & Fungus-growers (soil or leaf litter nesting) \\\\
Camponotus atriceps & 40 & Generalist omnivores (dominant or opportunistic in soil, leaf litter, or arboreal) \\\\
Crematogaster sp & 35 & Generalist omnivores (dominant or opportunistic in soil, leaf litter, or arboreal) \\\\
Cyphomyrmex minutus & 30 & Fungus-growers (soil or leaf litter nesting) \\\\
Cyphomyrmex rimosus & 28 & Fungus-growers (soil or leaf litter nesting) \\\\
Ectatomma edentatum & 25 & Generalist predators (dominant or cryptic in soil or leaf litter) \\\\
\\bottomrule
\\end{tabular}
\\end{table}
\\section{Comparison with Existing Software}
To our knowledge, no other \\proglang{R} package provides an integrated suite of functions specifically tailored for ant community analysis, including guild classification, exotic and endemic species detection, and rarity assessment. While packages such as \\pkg{vegan} \\citep{Oksanen2022} and \\pkg{FD} \\citep{Laliberte2014} offer powerful tools for multivariate analysis and functional diversity, they do not predefine functional groups based on myrmecological knowledge nor incorporate curated databases of invasion status or endemism. \\pkg{AntClassify} thus fills a unique niche by automating workflows that were previously performed manually, thereby increasing reproducibility and reducing analytical burden. Its modular design also allows users to integrate its outputs with existing packages for further analysis.
\\section{Conclusion}
\\pkg{AntClassify} provides a comprehensive, reproducible, and user-friendly framework for analyzing ant communities, with a focus on functional guild classification, exotic species detection, endemism, and rarity. By embedding curated ecological databases and offering multiple classification options, the package supports a wide range of research questions in biodiversity, community ecology, and conservation. The associated \\pkg{UrbanAnts} Shiny app enhances transparency and educational outreach. As the project continues, we plan to expand the databases and add new classification schemes, making the tool increasingly valuable for myrmecologists worldwide. The package is open source and freely available on CRAN and GitHub, encouraging contributions and collaborations.
\\section*{Acknowledgments}
We thank the Coordenação de Aperfeiçoamento de Pessoal de Nível Superior – Brasil (CAPES) for the doctoral scholarship granted to the first author (process no. 88887.821214/2023-00). We also thank all researchers who contributed to the underlying ant occurrence databases.
